LAYER 3 — They send raw IP packets
─────────────────────────────────────
Normal:  Your browser → TCP handshake → HTTP request
Attack:  Botnet       → raw IP packets, no handshake
                        just flood the network pipe

Tool:    hping3, scapy (craft raw packets)
How:     Spoof source IP so you can't block one address
         1000 bots × 1M packets = network pipe full
         Server never even sees the request
         Router/network dies first

LAYER 4 — They abuse TCP/UDP handshake
─────────────────────────────────────
SYN Flood:
  Normal TCP:   Client → SYN → Server replies SYN-ACK
                Client → ACK → connection open ✅
  Attack:       Bot    → SYN → Server replies SYN-ACK
                Bot never sends ACK ❌
                Server waits... waits... waits...
                10,000 half-open connections
                Server RAM full → crash

UDP Flood:
  Bot sends UDP packets to random ports
  Server checks each port → no app listening
  Server sends "port unreachable" back for each
  Server exhausted replying to junk

LAYER 7 — They send real HTTP requests
─────────────────────────────────────
HTTP Flood:
  Bot sends:  GET /home HTTP/1.1
              Host: yoursite.com
  Looks 100% like real user traffic
  Server processes each request fully
  Hits database, renders page, burns CPU
  1M requests/sec → server CPU 100% → down

Slowloris:
  Bot opens connection → sends headers slowly
  GET /home HTTP/1.1\r\n
  Host: yoursite.com\r\n
  ... sends one header every 10 seconds ...
  Never completes the request
  Server holds connection open waiting
  500 connections × slowloris = server full
  No real users can connect ❌
----------------
The key difference:

Layer 3  →  never reaches your server OS
Layer 4  →  reaches OS network stack, kills it
Layer 7  →  reaches your actual app, kills it

Layer 7 is hardest to block because the traffic looks exactly like real users — only the volume gives it away, which is why WAF rate limiting exists.
---------------------------------------

WAF alone — NOT enough for Layer 7 DDoS
─────────────────────────────────────────
WAF is designed for:
  SQL injection        ✅
  XSS                  ✅
  Bot fingerprinting   ✅
  Geo blocking         ✅
  Rate limiting        ✅ (but limited)

WAF is NOT designed for:
  Massive HTTP floods   ❌ (volume too high)
  Slowloris at scale    ❌
  Distributed botnet    ❌ (millions of IPs)

--------------------------------------------------

The problem with WAF rate limiting:
--------------------------------------------------
WAF rate limit:  block if > 2000 req/min per IP
DDoS attack:     1000 bots × 100 req/min each
                 = each bot stays under limit ✅
                 = total = 100,000 req/min     ❌
                 WAF never triggers, server dies
